'''The King of Love My Shepherd Is''' is an 1868 hymn with lyrics written by [[Sir Henry Williams Baker, 3rd Baronet|Henry Baker]], based on the Welsh version of [[Psalm 23]] and the work of [[Edmund Prys]].<ref>http://www.hymnary.org/text/yr_arglwydd_yw_fy_mugail_clau</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Francis Arthur Jones|title=Famous hymns and their authors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PdgNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA178|year=1903|publisher=Hodder and Stoughton|page=178}}</ref><ref>Towner, W. Sibley.  "'Without Our Aid Did He Us Make': Singing the Meaning of the Psalms". In {{cite book|author1=Patrick D. Miller|author2=Brent A. Strawn|author3=Nancy R. Bowen|title=A God So Near: Essays on Old Testament Theology in Honor of Patrick D. Miller|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hO2KvSuhzdkC&pg=PA26|year=2003|publisher=Eisenbrauns|isbn=978-1-57506-067-5|page=26}}</ref> It is sung to three different melodies: Dominus Regit Me, a traditional Irish tune called St. Columba, and Remsen, the Welsh original.<ref>http://www.hymnary.org/tune/remsen_thomas</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Harvard University Hymn Book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=feDyJOLd-AYC&pg=PA195|year=2007|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-02696-4|pages=195â€“196}}</ref> Henry Baker's last words were reportedly lyrics from this hymn.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Morgan|title=Then Sings My Soul: 150 of the World's Greatest Hymn Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4fJLL2VXuSUC&pg=PA169|year=2003|publisher=Thomas Nelson Inc|isbn=978-1-4185-7824-4|page=169}}</ref>

